        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec 31. 1876</date>
                    <salute>My dear Häckel,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It is very kind of you to send me your new &amp; improved edition of ‘Anthropogenie’ &amp;c’ &amp; I thank you heartily.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I sent you lately a copy of my new book on cross-fertilisation, as I thought that you would like to possess the complete series of my works.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> But I knew that the present one would not interest you; &amp; do not waste your time by acknowledging its receipt.</p>
<p>My dear Häckel | Yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10738.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Ernst Haeckel, 30 December 1876</ref> and n. 6. CD’s copy of the third edition of <hi rend="italic">Anthropogenie: oder, Entwickelungsgeschichte des Menschen</hi> (Anthropogeny, or the developmental history of humans; Haeckel 1877) is in the Darwin Library–Down.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Haeckel’s name is on CD’s presentation list for <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8595.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Cross and self fertilisation</hi></ref> (see Appendix III). Their letters crossed in the post; Haeckel acknowledged receiving the book in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10738.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 30 December 1876</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
